<title>SOUTH AFRICA: South Africa lists foreign arms clients.</title>
<headline>South Africa lists foreign arms clients.</headline>
<dateline>CAPE TOWN 1997-05-08</dateline>
<text>
<p>South Africa has sold arms to 73 countries including the United States, China and Russia in the past three years, Defence Minister Joe Modise said on Thursday.</p>
<p>The countries, listed in response to a question in parliament, did not include any the United States accuses of state terrorism -- North Korea, Iran, Iraq, Syria or Libya.</p>
<p>A diplomatic row erupted between Washington and Pretoria earlier this year when it emerged that a South African company was trying to sell Syria equipment to upgrade its battle tanks.</p>
<p>Modise said that since democratic elections in April 1994, South Africa had sold arms to several countries in the Gulf and Middle East, including Israel, Kuwait, Lebanon and Egypt.</p>
<p>He said South Africa had earned 1.4 billion rand ($310 million) in arms exports in 1995. Last year the country spent 3.4 billion rand on buying arms, most of them acquired from domestic manufacturers, Modise said.</p>
<p>($=4.46 rand)</p>
